.TH strdupa 3 (date) "Linux man-pages (unreleased)"
.SH NAME
strdupa, strndupa \- string duplicate using alloca
.SH LIBRARY
Standard C library
.RI ( libc ,\~ \-lc )
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.BR "#define _GNU_SOURCE" "  /* See feature_test_macros(7) */"
.B #include <string.h>
.P
.BI "char *strdupa(const char *" s );
.BR "char *strndupa(" "size_t n;"
.BI "              const char " s [ n "], size_t " n );
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.TP
.BR strdupa ()
.BR strdupa ()
is similar to
.BR strdup (3),
but uses
.BR alloca (3)
to allocate the buffer.
.IP
It is equivalent to
.IP
.in +4n
.EX
strcpy(alloca(strlen(s) + 1), s)
.EE
.in
.TP
.BR strndupa ()
.BR strndupa ()
is similar to
.BR strndupa (3),
but uses
.BR alloca (3)
to allocate the buffer.
.IP
It is equivalent to
.IP
.in +4n
.EX
strncat(strcpy(alloca(n + 1), ""), s, n)
.EE
.in
.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
these macros return
a pointer to the duplicated string.
.SH ATTRIBUTES
For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see
.BR attributes (7).
.TS
allbox;
lbx lb lb
l l l.
